---
description: Prefer one logical line for simple guards, expressions, literals, and trivial JSX when readable
alwaysApply: true
priority: high
---

# Single-line simple expressions (TS / JS / JSX)

Keep **simple** code **compact** (short declarations, small ternaries, obvious callbacks, trivial **`t("…")`** / single **`{}` child** in JSX) when it stays readable. Use **semicolons** per **`semicolons`**. Do not fight **Prettier** / `printWidth`.

**Signatures:** One line when it fits. Prefer a small named props type over a huge inline type in the signature.

## `if` / `else`

- **No `else`:** one branch, **one** statement → braceless allowed (`if (ok) refresh();`). **Several** statements → **`{ }`**.
- **With `else`:** **always** **`{ }`** on **every** limb, even for a single statement each (including **`else if`** segments). Avoid mixing braceless **`if`** with braced **`else`**.

## Early-return ladders (`if (...) return …;` only)

- **No** blank line **between** consecutive one-line **`if (...) return`** rows.
- **One** blank line **after** the **last** such row when something else follows in the same block (`const …`, plain **`return`**, **`await`**, **`{`** …).
- **Never** insert a blank between a normal statement and the **next** **`if (...) return`** (e.g. `const trimmed = s.trim()` then **`if (!ok) return null`** stuck together).

The last **`if (...) return`** in a block gets **no** trailing blank when nothing follows. A branch with **several** statements uses **`{ }`** with **one statement per line** (no fused **`a(); return;`**).

```typescript
if (needsAuth) return null;
if (!session) return null;

return dashboard();

const trimmed = value.trim();
if (!/^\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}$/.test(trimmed)) return null;

return trimmed;
```

**Non-return** compact **`if`** one-liners: optional blank before the next line—clarity beats dogma.

**Two-step exits** (**`setError(…)`** then **`return`**): **`return`** on its own line inside a **`{ }`** branch.

## Strings & JSX

Strings: keep one-line `"... "` unless you want a multi-line template.

JSX: static text ⇒ often one line (`<button type="button">Save</button>`); one trivial **`{}`** expression child can stay on one line when the opening tag fits; heavier trees ⇒ wrap normally.

## Long / noisy code

Prefer normal wrapping when props, objects, JSX, or templates would be cramped.

## Scope

**New and edited** code only; skip drive-by reformat of untouched areas.
